  1. A simple method of seeing if the information follows the 68-95-99.7 rule is to just count the number of heights that fall within those standard deviations, then calculate what percentage that is.
heights <- c(54, 55, 56, 56, 57, 58, 58, 59, 60, 60, 60, 61, 61, 62, 62, 63, 63, 63, 64, 65, 65, 67, 67, 69, 73)

m <- 61.52
sd <- 4.58

one.sd <- heights[(m - sd) < heights & heights < (m + sd)]
two.sd <- heights[(m - 2 * sd) < heights & heights < (m + 2 * sd)]
three.sd <- heights[(m - 3 * sd) < heights & heights < (m + 3 * sd)]

length(one.sd) / length(heights)
## [1] 0.68
length(two.sd) / length(heights)
## [1] 0.96
length(three.sd) / length(heights)
## [1] 1

Yes, this data seems to conform to the 68-95-99.7 rule, as it breaks down to 68-96-1

  1. I believe it’s close enough. It conforms to the 68-95-99.7 rule, and the graph is close to a normal distribution. The simulation plot has two extreme outliers, but the bulk remain near the line.

sqrt((1 - 0.02) / 0.02^2)

  1. We will use the negative binomial distribution: \({n - 1 \choose k - 1} p^k (1 - p)^{n - k}\) with n = 10 and k = 3
fac <- factorial(9)/(factorial(2) * factorial(7))
fac * 0.15^3 * 0.85^7
## [1] 0.03895012
  1. As the serves are independent, her probability of a success on the tenth serve is simply 0.15, or p. It’s the same as asking what is the odds of getting heads on the nth coin flip, given that you have two heads already. The other flips don’t matter.

If the question asked “What is the probability that she has three successful serves in ten attempts”, then we can utilize the binomial distribution to solve. In this situation, the answer would be:

fac.serve <- factorial(10) / (factorial(3) * factorial(7))
fac.serve * 0.15^3 * 0.85^7
## [1] 0.1298337
  1. Part a is asking for a specific ordering. It wants to know what is the probability that on the 10th try she will make her 3rd successful serve. Part b is more concerned with three successes in ten failures, and we can assume that the order doesn’t matter.
